title.narrative: Assessing the feasibility to produce energy from Water hyacinth plants in Sogakope, Ghana

description.narrative: Invasive species like the water hyacinth have become a serious threat to global biodiversity and countries like Ghana in particular, as they lack natural enemies and have a reproduction rate of 5 to 15 days. They only stop growing when they run out of resources, wiping out native species, disrupting entire ecosystems, covering a water body in a matter of months and in turn causing major economic and ecological damage and human - and animal suffering. Unmanaged water hyacinth infestations can lead to loss of food and water production, loss of transportation facilities and outbreaks of diseases caused by insects which hide in the plant mass, threatening entire local communities. Solving that problem needs ongoing and systematic effort which require resources but many countries and governments do not have the funds for a systematic and permanent solution. Dutch company Millennium Bio Energy (MBE) has developed a circular solution using Anaerobic Digestion (AD) of biomass that addresses both the problem of systematically removing the water weed as well as the problem of financing. MBE maintains the water ways and produces value from the biowaste with which the cost of maintenance is more than covered. More importantly, these AD products can be converted into heat, electricity, gas, CO2, fibers and fertilisers, offering a circular solution for other problems countries like Ghana are facing.To prepare for future investments in a pilot installation in Sogakope, Ghana, Technical Assistance (DGGF) provided support for a technical and financial feasibility study. This included a pre-project part in which the critical conditions for a successful pilot are tested: the location on which a pilot can be built, construction criteria are analysed, a customer for the energy is found, legal and regulatory conditions are validated and a local partner is found with whom MBE can operate legally in Ghana. The project was successful and resulted in the selection of a suitable location in the Lower Volta River, customer acquisition, partner selection and formal permission from the ministry of Environment to extract the water hyacinth biomass. Further investments in a pilot powerplant are currently being prepared and is expected to open mid-2020. When the pilot proves successful, upscaling the powerplant has the potential to supply over 1,000,000 people with energy, create 800 jobs and provide an income stream for the country whilst protecting its ecosystems and local water communities and reducing emissions.
